05037nam a22005775i 9780801463617DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20112013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014636177 a10.7591/97808014636172doi  a(DE-B1597)481753  a(OCoLC)987942388  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHD4456b.B35 2010eb 7aPOL0440002bisacsh04a363.6/12221 aBakker, Karen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPrivatizing Water :bGovernance Failure and the World's Urban Water Crisis /cKaren Bakker. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b21 halftones, 13 tables, 6 charts/graphs, 3 maps, 3 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures and Tables -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations and Acronyms -- tDefining “Privatization”: A Note on Terminology -- tIntroduction: Privatization and the Urban Water Crisis -- tPart I. Development, Urbanization, and the Governance of Thirst -- t1. Governance Failure: Reframing the Urban Water Supply Crisis -- t2. Material Emblems of Citizenship: Creating Public Water -- t3. Watering the Thirsty Poor: The Water Privatization Debate -- t4. Citizens without a City: The Techno-Politics of Urban Water Governance -- tPart II. Beyond Privatization: Debating Alternatives -- t5. Protesting Privatization: Transnational Struggles over the Human Right to Water -- t6. Commons versus Commodities: The Ambiguous Merits of Community Water-Supply Management -- t7. Politics and Biopolitics: Debating Ecological Governance -- tConclusion: Beyond Privatization -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWater supply privatization was emblematic of the neoliberal turn in development policy in the 1990s. Proponents argued that the private sector could provide better services at lower costs than governments; opponents questioned the risks involved in delegating control over a life-sustaining resource to for-profit companies. Private-sector activity was most concentrated—and contested—in large cities in developing countries, where the widespread lack of access to networked water supplies was characterized as a global crisis.In Privatizing Water, Karen Bakker focuses on three questions: Why did privatization emerge as a preferred alternative for managing urban water supply? Can privatization fulfill its proponents' expectations, particularly with respect to water supply to the urban poor? And, given the apparent shortcomings of both privatization and conventional approaches to government provision, what are the alternatives? In answering these questions, Bakker engages with broader debates over the role of the private sector in development, the role of urban communities in the provision of "public" services, and the governance of public goods. She introduces the concept of "governance failure" as a means of exploring the limitations facing both private companies and governments.Critically examining a range of issues—including the transnational struggle over the human right to water, the "commons" as a water-supply-management strategy, and the environmental dimensions of water privatization—Privatizing Water is a balanced exploration of a critical issue that affects billions of people around the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aMunicipal water supplyxPolitical aspects. 0aPrivatization. 0aRight to water. 0aWater utilitiesxDeregulation. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aSociology & Social Science. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Environmental Policy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist